body:
Useful in instances where a command takes an exact amount of arguments. 

Avoids calling both min and max args:
```rust
command("cmd", |c| c
    .min_args(1)
    .max_args(1)
    // ...
```

And also avoids doing manual checks in commands:
```rust
command!(cmd(_ctx, msg, args) {
    if args.len() != 1 {
        // print message or just return
    }
    // ...
});
```

I figured something like this would be nice to have. There are a few places in my bot where I take an optional url and an optional integer, and it leaves me with ugly code like this that is still somewhat buggy: 

```rust
let (url, width) = match args.len() {
    0 => (msg.author.face(), 80),
    1 => {
        if let Ok(num) = args[0].parse::<u64>() {
            (msg.author.face(), num)
        } else {
            if let Ok(user) = args.single_n::<User>() {
                (user.face(), 80)
            } else {
                (args[0].clone(), 80)
            }
        }
    }
    2 | _ => {
        if let Ok(user) = args.single_n::<User>() {
            (user.face(), args[1].parse::<u64>().unwrap_or(80))
        } else {
            (args[0].clone(), args[1].parse::<u64>().unwrap_or(80))
        }
    }
};
```

With these methods, it now looks like this: 

```rust
let width = args.find::<u64>().unwrap_or(80);
let url = args.find::<User>()
    .and_then(|user| Ok(user.face()))
    .unwrap_or_else(|_|
        args.single::<String>().unwrap_or(msg.author.face()));
```

Basic implementation, open to changes.

Usage:

```rust
use serenity::client::CACHE;
use serenity::model::permissions::*;
let cache = CACHE.read().expect("Could not read cache.");

// Pass empty permissions to get a url without the added "&permissions=" section
let no_perm_url = cache.user.invite_url(Permissions::empty());

// Pass in permissions to get them added to the end of the url.
let perm_url = cache.user.invite_url(READ_MESSAGES | SEND_MESSAGES);
```
